  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Money laundering is a serious federal crime in the United States, and the penalties for it can be severe. Under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act (MLCA) of 1986**, as well as related statutes, the penalties for money laundering include:\n\n1. **Imprisonment**:\n   - Individuals convicted of money laundering can face up to **20 years in federal prison** for each violation. In cases involving terrorism financing or other aggravating factors, the maximum penalty can increase.\n\n2. **Fines**:\n   - For individuals, fines can reach **$500,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds**, whichever is greater.\n   - For financial institutions or businesses, fines can be much higher, up to **$1 million or twice the value of the laundered funds**, whichever is greater.\n\n3. **Asset Forfeiture**:\n   - The government may seize and forfeit any property, funds, or assets involved in or derived from money laundering activities.\n\n4. **Civil Penalties**:\n   - In addition to criminal penalties, individuals or entities may face civil fines for violations of the Bank Secrecy Act or other anti-money laundering laws.\n\n5. **Enhanced Penalties for Aggravating Factors**:\n   - Penalties can be increased if the money laundering involves large sums of money, is part of an organized criminal enterprise, or is linked to terrorist activities.\n\n6. **Additional Consequences**:\n   - Convictions for money laundering can also result in reputational damage, loss of professional licenses, and increased scrutiny from regulatory agencies.\n\nThe severity of the penalties depends on factors such as the amount of money laundered, the nature of the underlying criminal activity, and whether the individual or entity has prior convictions. Prosecutions for money laundering are often pursued in conjunction with other charges, such as fraud, drug trafficking, or tax evasion. If you are facing charges, it is crucial to consult with an experienced attorney.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
